markets, or produce altogether new financial instruments to create change. Using examples from the economic and social histories of 19th-century America and Italy, two decentralized polities where challenges to sound banking originated from above and below, this book reveals the collective tactics that conservative bankers devise to legitimize strict boundaries around credit-and the transgressive strategies that wildcat bankers employ in their challenge to this restrictive stance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aBanks and bankingxSocial aspectsvCase studies. 0aBanks and bankingxSocial aspectszItalyxHistoryy19th century. 0aBanks and bankingxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aCreditxSocial aspectsvCase studies. 0aFinancexSocial aspectsvCase studies. 4aBanks. 4aBoundaries. 4aConflict. 4aCredit. 4aElites. 4aFinance. 4aIdeology. 4aLegitimacy. 4aMarkets. 4aMoney. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Banks & Banking.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804785556zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804785556423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804785556.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles